            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-slate-50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-indigo-700">2nd digit</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">TEER category (0-5)</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3"><strong>1</strong> = TEER 1 (university degree typically required)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-white">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-indigo-700">3rd digit</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Major group subdivision</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3"><strong>2</strong> = Computer and information systems professionals</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="bg-slate-50">
              <td class="px-4 py-3 font-bold text-indigo-700">4th &amp; 5th digits</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3">Specific unit group</td>
              <td class="px-4 py-3"><strong>32</strong> = Software developers and programmers</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>
        This structure means you can quickly identify the TEER level of any NOC code by looking at the <strong>second digit</strong>. A code starting with "21" is a TEER 1 occupation in the natural and applied sciences category, while a code starting with "63" is a TEER 3 occupation in sales and services.
      </p>

